        <exercise xml:id="auto_9dmb3ojn">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_zghkkr1z">
                    The figure below shows an isosceles
                    triangle in which <m>AB = AC = 9\, cm</m>.
                    Angle <m>BAC</m> is <m>100^\circ</m>. Calculate the
                    length of BC.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_t7dfzz2p">
                    <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image label="Triangle15">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
                                    
                                    % Define points
                                    \coordinate (A) at (3,4);
                                    \coordinate (B) at (0,0);
                                    \coordinate (C) at (6,0);

                                    % Draw the triangle
                                    \draw [very thick,fill=white] (B) node[left] {$B$} -- (A) node[above] {$A$} -- (C) node[right] {$C$} -- cycle;

                                    % Mark equal sides
                                    \draw [very thick] (1.3,2.1) -- ++(0.35,-0.35);
                                    \draw [very thick](4.7,2.1) -- ++(-0.35,-0.35);

                                    % Angle at A
                                    \draw (2.4,3.2) arc[start angle=210,end angle=330,radius=0.7];
                                    \node[below] at (3,2.9) { $100^\circ$};

                                    % Side label
                                    \node[right] at (4.7,2) { 9 cm};
                                    \node[left] at (1.3,2) { 9 cm};
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                            
                        </image>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_0ihocg6o">
                    Dropping a perpendicular from <m>A</m> to <m>BC</m> bisects the angle at <m>A</m>, so each right triangle has hypotenuse <m>9\,\text{cm}</m>
                    and acute angle <m>50^\circ</m>. Thus <m>\dfrac{BC}{2} = 9\sin 50^\circ</m>, so <m>BC = 2 \times 9\sin 50^\circ \approx 13.8\,\text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
